25:48.880 --> 25:49.630
...prison.

25:50.460 --> 25:51.840
It’s some guy from the high
school

25:51.960 --> 25:53.050
he called and let us know.

25:56.130 --> 25:57.180
Hold on Bonnie--

25:57.300 --> 25:58.300
Good morning ma’am.

25:58.680 --> 25:59.930
I’m Stan Deen,
Nathan’s teacher.

26:00.430 --> 26:02.060
Is he here?

26:04.270 --> 26:05.640
Nathan’s teacher.--

26:06.520 --> 26:07.940
I don’t know.

26:09.150 --> 26:10.570
Hey, what are you doing here?

26:10.980 --> 26:12.610
Hey Nate, hi.

26:13.780 --> 26:16.780
Gee, I hoped I’d see you
back in class by now.

26:16.910 --> 26:19.280
He’s got a job.
He don’t need no school.

26:19.570 --> 26:21.080
Dropping out of school, huh?

26:21.410 --> 26:24.410
Uh oh. I’ll be out of
a job if that gets around.

26:27.870 --> 26:31.040
Nate, you
gotta get back in school.

26:31.920 --> 26:33.590
What’s gonna happen
when you go on trial?

26:33.920 --> 26:34.800
Whaddya mean?

26:35.090 --> 26:36.300
When he goes to
court, he has to show

26:36.420 --> 26:38.090
the judge he’s not
that person anymore.

26:38.680 --> 26:40.640
And the best way to do that

26:40.760 --> 26:43.470
is to go back to
school and graduate.

26:43.850 --> 26:45.310
New Holland’s too far.

26:45.430 --> 26:47.230
His car’s impounded
till the trial.

26:47.350 --> 26:49.600
What she means is,
they put up my bail.

26:50.150 --> 26:51.270
I gotta work
for them to pay it back.

26:51.440 --> 26:53.530
Bonnie, I’ll call you back.

26:55.690 --> 26:58.860
We can’t put up bail
every time he gets in trouble.

26:59.160 --> 27:01.530
Well, plenty of
kids get a part-time job.

27:02.530 --> 27:07.540
Nate, where was the foster home
you were staying at before?

27:09.670 --> 27:10.330
Nathan?

27:13.130 --> 27:16.800
I wasn’t in a foster home.
I was living in my car.

27:17.550 --> 27:18.430
Your car?

27:19.180 --> 27:20.840
What do you mean your car?

27:21.140 --> 27:24.310
You lived in your car? Where?

27:24.890 --> 27:26.350
I don’t know. Quiet places.

27:27.100 --> 27:28.350
Fields, mostly.

27:29.440 --> 27:30.400
How’d you eat?

27:30.600 --> 27:32.520
I didn’t. Not really.

27:32.650 --> 27:33.860
That Hershey bar
you gave me was the

27:33.980 --> 27:35.780
only meal I had
in like three days.

27:35.900 --> 27:36.780
Oh my gosh.

27:37.240 --> 27:38.650
Why do you think
I was on the track team?

27:39.950 --> 27:41.910
So I could shower, Mr. Deen.

27:43.280 --> 27:46.370
Nate, we have got
to get you back in school.

27:46.490 --> 27:48.460
Why? Show’em I’m a con?

27:49.250 --> 27:50.670
What are you doin’ in here?

27:51.290 --> 27:52.630
Oh, Gosh.

27:53.880 --> 27:55.800
This is Nathan’s teacher.

27:57.170 --> 27:59.340
He wants to get
Nathan back in school.

27:59.670 --> 28:02.050
Yeah, that’s right.

28:04.680 --> 28:05.760
Who is this?

28:06.600 --> 28:09.230
Nathan’s mother. Gloria.

28:10.730 --> 28:11.690
She’s beautiful.

28:11.850 --> 28:13.350
She died when I was six.

28:14.560 --> 28:16.480
Terrible accident. Car accident.

28:17.190 --> 28:18.530
Died instant like.

28:18.650 --> 28:19.820
Nanny...

28:20.150 --> 28:21.320
Don’t start that again.

28:21.820 --> 28:25.200
You can’t keep making
up stories about what happened.

28:25.950 --> 28:28.700
Right when he was little,
he made up stories.

28:29.450 --> 28:30.620
Upsetting people.

28:31.790 --> 28:33.580
After she died, we couldn’t...

28:35.710 --> 28:38.960
a little child
needs a lot of keepin’.

28:39.300 --> 28:41.590
We thought the orphanage
would give him a good home.

28:41.930 --> 28:43.010
My Lord.

28:43.800 --> 28:45.850
I’m sorry, but
what about the father?

28:46.140 --> 28:47.930
We don’t speak
about that piece of trash.

28:48.470 --> 28:50.140
As I tell Nathaniel,

28:50.270 --> 28:53.350
he better forget that man
ever drew a living breath.

28:54.230 --> 28:55.730
Otherwise,
people will think

28:55.900 --> 28:58.150
the apple don’t
fall far from the tree.

28:58.860 --> 29:00.900
She shouldn’t have took
up with him in the first place.

29:01.610 --> 29:03.070
She brought it on herself.

29:04.700 --> 29:06.030
C’mon, Nathaniel.

29:10.580 --> 29:12.040
Nate. Nate.

29:13.040 --> 29:14.210
Here’s my number.

29:14.330 --> 29:16.960
If you change your mind,
I promise you...

29:19.340 --> 29:20.670
We’ll figure this out.

29:22.470 --> 29:23.170
Thanks.

29:38.570 --> 29:39.400
I know.

29:39.770 --> 29:42.070
It’s just a little upsetting
when the first person

29:42.190 --> 29:44.280
isn’t somebody
faceless in the newspaper.

29:45.070 --> 29:46.200
But someone you know...

29:47.450 --> 29:48.700
someone you care about.

29:49.870 --> 29:52.120
If Charlie is chosen
and we succeed,

29:52.330 --> 29:54.370
he will have more
than a new life.

29:54.580 --> 29:55.750
He will have a life.

29:56.290 --> 29:57.420
And if we fail,

29:57.540 --> 30:00.340
he will have made a greater
contribution to mankind

30:00.460 --> 30:03.050
than most normal people
could ever hope to do.

30:03.550 --> 30:05.380
You think he has
a future as an actor.

30:05.590 --> 30:08.180
I don’t think Barnaby
has any future as an actor.

30:08.300 --> 30:09.050
I mean...

30:10.810 --> 30:11.510
But...

30:13.680 --> 30:15.480
I can see him
disappearing into his shell,

30:15.690 --> 30:17.190
you know, this
thing with his knee, and...

30:18.480 --> 30:19.690
There’s a terrific kid there.

30:21.980 --> 30:23.280
And if I can help...

30:24.490 --> 30:26.360
even at Flowers
for Algernon’s expense...

30:27.950 --> 30:30.990
then... I mean, what the heck?

30:33.330 --> 30:35.710
No one walks out
of a Stan Deen production.

30:36.370 --> 30:37.170
Except me.

30:48.840 --> 30:51.850
Hey, hi, Mr. Deen.
It’s Nate. Nate Williams.

30:52.850 --> 30:53.560
Uh...

30:54.470 --> 30:56.100
I’ve been thinking about
what you said.

30:57.520 --> 30:58.940
I’d like to come back to school.

31:30.840 --> 31:33.550
Before we do this,
I need something from you.

31:34.060 --> 31:35.770
I need to know you trust me.

31:36.140 --> 31:37.100
I trust you.

31:38.600 --> 31:39.480
Let’s tell
each other something

31:39.600 --> 31:41.480
about ourselves
neither of us knows.

31:42.440 --> 31:43.650
Okay? I’ll go first.

31:44.900 --> 31:45.610
Uh...

31:48.990 --> 31:50.360
I wanted to be a movie star.

31:51.530 --> 31:52.280
What?

31:52.490 --> 31:55.870
Yep. I was gonna
be the next James Deen.

31:56.240 --> 31:57.830
I already had the last name.

32:03.460 --> 32:04.790
You don’t know
who that is, do you?

32:04.920 --> 32:05.800
mm-mmm

32:06.710 --> 32:10.010
I quit my teaching job
and I moved out to California.

32:10.680 --> 32:11.800
Why’d you come back?

32:12.930 --> 32:14.220
Didn’t work out.

32:15.680 --> 32:16.970
Okay, your turn.

32:20.180 --> 32:21.730
I don’t like reading out loud.

32:22.440 --> 32:24.980
I already know that.
I also know you’re good at it.

32:25.110 --> 32:26.610
Okay, what’s something
no one knows?

32:28.690 --> 32:29.900
I like photography.

32:32.570 --> 32:34.160
-Let’s go with that.
-Yeah, can we go now?

32:38.370 --> 32:40.500
Does Mrs. Baker
know you like photography?

32:42.370 --> 32:43.710
Okay, got it. Not cool.

33:19.580 --> 33:20.580
Wow.

33:21.160 --> 33:22.460
Pretty great, huh?

33:22.870 --> 33:24.420
It’s a mid-century ranch.

33:24.670 --> 33:25.960
No. No.

33:27.670 --> 33:29.090
It’s more of a dump
than my car, Mr. Deen.

33:32.420 --> 33:34.380
Okay. You’re
sleeping on the couch.

33:34.510 --> 33:36.220
You can just push that stuff--

33:39.010 --> 33:40.720
The couch is
quite comfortable.

33:41.470 --> 33:43.310
but I’ll make some
house calls tomorrow

33:43.430 --> 33:45.940
and see if I can
find something better for you,

33:46.100 --> 33:47.060
your highness.

33:48.020 --> 33:49.070
Is this your mom?

33:49.270 --> 33:51.690
Huh? Yeah, my dad took that.

33:51.900 --> 33:53.440
He was a photographer, too.

33:53.780 --> 33:54.650
Professional.

33:55.280 --> 33:56.280
Where is your mom?

33:57.450 --> 33:58.740
She, uh...

33:59.530 --> 34:00.950
She passed.

34:02.450 --> 34:04.500
Last... last January.

34:05.080 --> 34:05.830
Sorry

34:05.960 --> 34:07.830
It’s all right. It’s all right.

34:07.960 --> 34:10.210
You know,
she had a big stroke,

34:10.340 --> 34:12.210
I guess,
about eight years ago, and...

34:14.340 --> 34:15.340
I looked after her.

34:16.930 --> 34:17.840
Can I use your bathroom?

34:18.010 --> 34:21.350
Yeah, yeah. Sure, of course.
It’s just through there.

34:45.290 --> 34:50.040
♪ It’s time to
start a show tonight ♪

34:50.170 --> 34:51.500
Hey! There you are.

34:51.750 --> 34:53.340
I was gonna
send out a search party.

34:54.050 --> 34:56.090
We are having pasta for dinner.

34:56.380 --> 34:58.010
Now, the secret to good pasta.

34:58.130 --> 34:59.300
I don’t like pasta.

35:00.340 --> 35:01.640
That’s because you
haven’t had mine.

35:02.510 --> 35:04.270
Now, the way
they do it in Italia

35:04.470 --> 35:08.190
is you add the
spaghetti to the sauce,

35:08.310 --> 35:09.810
and not the
sauce to the spaghetti.

35:09.940 --> 35:11.520
Mama mia no signori, ah.

35:11.690 --> 35:12.440
You know how to cook?

35:12.650 --> 35:13.320
Yeah.

35:13.440 --> 35:17.400
My mom was not a fan of
Chinese takeout or pizza, so...

35:19.570 --> 35:20.780
Is this your dad?

35:21.990 --> 35:22.830
Yeah.

35:24.160 --> 35:25.750
He used to make
me carry all his gear.

35:26.160 --> 35:27.120
I hated it.

35:27.460 --> 35:29.290
He thought it was hysterical.

35:30.670 --> 35:32.080
That was in
the Blue Mountains.

35:32.210 --> 35:33.130
He was a photographer.

35:33.250 --> 35:35.050
Yeah. He was
the main photographer

35:35.170 --> 35:36.800
for the
Hamilton Watch Company.

35:36.920 --> 35:38.050
What about your dad?

35:38.590 --> 35:40.180
Yeah, which one?
I had a lot of ’em.

35:40.510 --> 35:42.140
Right. No, I meant your real--

35:42.260 --> 35:43.050
What’s this?

35:43.300 --> 35:45.010
That was a play I was in.

35:45.260 --> 35:47.980
My mom kept all that stuff
I sent home from Hollywood.

35:48.310 --> 35:50.020
What kind of
work did your dad do?

35:50.190 --> 35:51.310
Were you in any movies?

35:51.560 --> 35:53.270
I was in one.

35:53.650 --> 35:56.360
The sum total of my role
was getting punched in the face.

35:57.570 --> 35:58.900
I’d like to see that.

36:00.450 --> 36:03.870
Ecco! Time to put
the spaghetti in the sauce.

36:25.100 --> 36:26.060
Morning.

36:28.810 --> 36:29.930
-Morning, Jen.
-Morning.

36:30.060 --> 36:32.350
Travis. Travis.

36:33.020 --> 36:34.190
Thank you.

36:38.190 --> 36:39.320
Morning, Renee.

36:39.940 --> 36:42.660
We are here to sign this
young man back into school.

36:46.700 --> 36:51.830
So, you have a
convicted felon living with you.

36:52.420 --> 36:54.580
Until I can find him
somewhere more permanent.

36:55.210 --> 36:58.090
And actually, Miriam,
he’s out on bail.

36:58.380 --> 37:01.220
Oh, sorry.
Soon-to-be-convicted.

37:02.680 --> 37:03.590
Is there a problem?

37:03.760 --> 37:05.050
Yes, there is, Stan.

37:05.430 --> 37:06.970
You have brought him back here.

37:07.350 --> 37:09.310
What exactly do you
know about this kid?

37:10.060 --> 37:11.560
I know he likes photography.

37:12.600 --> 37:14.020
Had you spotted that, Miriam?

37:14.190 --> 37:15.100
No, bet you hadn’t.

37:15.230 --> 37:18.610
You should be very careful
taking in a kid like that.

37:18.940 --> 37:22.530
If things start going missing,
don’t complain or come to us.

37:22.740 --> 37:26.700
Guys, I know exactly
why he was arrested, all right?

37:27.450 --> 37:31.500
I also know that he was living
out of his car for two years.

37:31.750 --> 37:34.500
Going hungry, only running track
so he could get a shower.

37:34.620 --> 37:37.080
Well, let the system
take care of him, Stan.

37:42.880 --> 37:46.550
You know, I didn’t understand
how no one saw this happening.

37:47.510 --> 37:51.560
But, you’ve all
just made that real clear.

37:51.970 --> 37:54.100
So, thank you.

37:55.440 --> 37:58.150
Today’s quote
is from Jonathan Swift...

37:58.270 --> 37:58.940
Hey...

37:59.070 --> 37:59.900
Yo, you’re back.

38:00.020 --> 38:01.230
Yeah, with a record.

38:02.150 --> 38:03.110
I owe you buddy.

38:03.320 --> 38:04.780
Yeah, I can’t hang out
with you, dude.

38:05.110 --> 38:06.490
I gotta stay
clean till the hearing.

38:07.200 --> 38:08.370
Yeah, here when you need me.

38:10.160 --> 38:11.160
Hey, hey, wait.

38:11.790 --> 38:12.620
Wait.

38:14.410 --> 38:15.920
I missed you so freaking much.

38:18.210 --> 38:19.210
I thought they kicked you out.

38:21.670 --> 38:22.760
Yeah, I’m turning around.

38:23.590 --> 38:25.010
Why did you lie to me?

38:26.300 --> 38:28.550
You were sleeping in
your car this whole time.

38:28.680 --> 38:31.140
So what? It’s pretty
freaking sweet, right?

38:31.640 --> 38:32.810
I can’t date you anymore.

38:33.810 --> 38:35.480
What? Hey...

38:36.940 --> 38:39.020
My dad said I can’t
see you anymore.

38:41.110 --> 38:42.230
What do you want?

38:43.570 --> 38:44.320
Huh?

38:47.910 --> 38:49.820
No, I can’t. I can’t.

38:50.700 --> 38:52.410
My dad can be real mean.

38:53.120 --> 38:54.370
He gave me no choice.

38:55.330 --> 38:56.000
Come on.

38:56.120 --> 38:57.790
No, this is it.
Really, I’m sorry.

38:57.920 --> 38:59.040
No. Tina.

39:00.630 --> 39:01.500
Tina!

39:02.170 --> 39:03.300
Ahh!

39:10.640 --> 39:11.640
What?

39:12.760 --> 39:13.430
Nate.

39:17.310 --> 39:18.140
Nate.

39:20.560 --> 39:22.110
Ah, great.

39:39.460 --> 39:42.380
Run, Nathan. Run.

39:47.760 --> 39:48.550
Nate.

39:50.720 --> 39:53.430
Oh, no. Nate, I’m not a runner.

39:53.720 --> 39:55.560
Have mercy. Nate.

39:56.310 --> 39:57.390
Oh, my lord.

39:59.890 --> 40:00.850
Stan?

40:01.440 --> 40:02.190
Stan.

40:03.440 --> 40:04.320
Come on.

40:06.440 --> 40:08.820
Hey. You okay?

40:09.450 --> 40:13.370
Yeah. I’m fine.
I just couldn’t run anymore.

40:15.370 --> 40:16.290
I can’t do this.

40:16.450 --> 40:18.000
Stan, I’m cursed.
Everyone’s against me.

40:18.450 --> 40:21.330
You’re not cursed,
but I won’t lie to you.

40:21.960 --> 40:23.580
This is going to be hard.

40:24.670 --> 40:27.590
Face everything
and deal with it, Nate.

40:27.710 --> 40:30.010
Running away
only delays the problem.

40:30.130 --> 40:31.090
I can’t.

40:31.590 --> 40:32.890
You can.

40:33.590 --> 40:35.180
This too shall pass.

40:35.430 --> 40:37.060
What does that even mean, Stan?

40:37.680 --> 40:41.770
It means that a year
from now, maybe even less,

40:42.650 --> 40:43.940
this won’t seem that important.

40:44.940 --> 40:46.150
Then why the
heck am I here, then?

40:46.440 --> 40:49.650
That’s a good question, Nate.
Why are you here?

40:50.900 --> 40:51.860
Girls and sports.

40:53.030 --> 40:56.330
That’s the wrong answer.
What’s the right answer, Stan?

40:56.450 --> 40:58.490
Why it’s to
keep him out of jail, Bob.

40:58.700 --> 41:01.080
You do realize that this

41:01.210 --> 41:03.790
is your only chance with
the judge, right?

41:06.210 --> 41:07.170
What do you get out of it?

41:08.340 --> 41:09.050
What?

41:12.300 --> 41:13.760
Everyone’s got an angle, Stan.

41:18.060 --> 41:20.720
Expelled! Seriously?

41:22.560 --> 41:24.190
He only just came back.

41:24.400 --> 41:27.020
I’m thinking about all
the students and their parents.

41:27.480 --> 41:28.820
I already had a
dozen calls about him

41:28.940 --> 41:30.440
coming back,
and I still took him in

41:30.900 --> 41:32.320
and on his first day,

41:32.440 --> 41:34.360
he rewards me by
punching out a window?

41:34.570 --> 41:36.160
Well, put yourself
in his shoes, John.

41:36.280 --> 41:38.080
Coming back here
after the way he left.

41:38.330 --> 41:40.490
Stan, your first
priority is to this school.

41:40.910 --> 41:42.500
You’re not a social worker.

41:42.750 --> 41:45.210
Is it? I mean, is it, though?

41:45.330 --> 41:48.710
Isn’t my first priority to
my students, all of them?

41:50.250 --> 41:51.590
You know, kids
come to me all the time,

41:51.710 --> 41:53.670
with some problem
they think is so big

41:53.800 --> 41:55.510
their whole life
is gonna be ruined,

41:55.630 --> 41:58.760
and I say to them, “Stand back.
Look at the big picture.

41:58.890 --> 41:59.810
You’ll get through this.

42:00.390 --> 42:01.430
One day you’ll look back at it

42:01.560 --> 42:02.980
and see it
wasn’t such a big deal.

42:03.680 --> 42:05.270
Your life
turned out just fine.”

42:06.900 --> 42:09.480
But you and I know this isn’t
a level playing field, John.

42:10.570 --> 42:12.480
Some kids are born
behind the eight ball,

42:13.690 --> 42:14.820
and we’re lying
to them when we say

42:14.950 --> 42:16.360
everything’s
gonna work out just fine.

42:18.160 --> 42:20.990
But don’t those kids deserve
the same chance as the others?

42:23.450 --> 42:26.210
I believe Nathan’s--

42:28.460 --> 42:30.130
There’s a good kid there.

42:32.380 --> 42:33.130
Please.

42:34.880 --> 42:36.130
Give him detention.

42:40.100 --> 42:41.930
Oh, my gosh.

42:45.560 --> 42:48.310
I think he’s gonna live
in detention until he graduates.

42:49.400 --> 42:51.440
So have you found
somewhere for him?

42:51.820 --> 42:54.570
No. No, I tried.

42:55.740 --> 42:57.200
There’s no room at the inn.

42:58.570 --> 42:59.370
You’ve gotta be careful.

43:00.570 --> 43:02.740
This is not the same
as being their teacher.

43:03.450 --> 43:04.160
I know that.

43:04.450 --> 43:05.290
No.

43:06.960 --> 43:07.750
You don’t.

43:08.830 --> 43:10.210
I had this student one time.

43:13.050 --> 43:16.510
She lost her dad, and then
her mom became an alcoholic.

43:17.470 --> 43:19.220
She completely shut down.

43:19.720 --> 43:20.890
Stopped showing up to school.

43:21.720 --> 43:23.310
So I tried to help.

43:24.600 --> 43:25.930
Had her come to the house.

43:27.020 --> 43:28.390
But, uh...

43:29.940 --> 43:31.730
It really affected
Robert and the girls.

43:34.480 --> 43:35.440
What did you do?

43:39.240 --> 43:41.070
I didn’t do anything.

43:43.200 --> 43:49.120
I watched her slip through
the cracks and into the system.

43:53.340 --> 43:54.920
I never saw her again.

44:26.870 --> 44:28.160
Okay.

44:31.670 --> 44:34.290
Please keep in mind,
no speaking unless spoken to.

44:34.460 --> 44:37.840
No arguing with the
Judge and look like a graduate.

44:38.340 --> 44:39.720
Do you have another tie?

44:41.760 --> 44:42.630
Never mind.

44:44.470 --> 44:45.680
You said this was good.

44:46.100 --> 44:48.220
Remember, this too shall pass.

44:50.560 --> 44:52.850
Mr. Deen? Is it Mr. Stan Deen?

44:53.810 --> 44:54.810
This is Mr. Deen, Your Honor.

44:54.940 --> 44:55.980
Yes, thank you, Council.

44:56.270 --> 44:57.940
Mr. Deen, I understand you are

44:58.070 --> 45:00.400
providing supervision
for the defendant?

45:01.070 --> 45:02.150
Yes, Your Honor.

45:02.280 --> 45:04.200
Thank you, Mr. Deen, and
the defendant’s grandparents

45:04.320 --> 45:05.990
are prepared to
assign custody to you?

45:06.280 --> 45:07.370
Yes, we will.

45:09.160 --> 45:11.790
And are you willing to
take on this responsibility?

45:12.040 --> 45:13.250
I am, Your Honor.

45:18.210 --> 45:19.420
Nathan Williams.

45:21.880 --> 45:24.800
This charge carries an automatic
two-year minimum sentence.

45:25.010 --> 45:27.050
I feel encouraged by
your return to school

45:27.180 --> 45:28.510
and your plans to graduate.

45:30.140 --> 45:32.640
I am minded to suspend
the bulk of that sentence.

45:32.770 --> 45:35.690
And I note this is your first
appearance before the court.

45:38.610 --> 45:40.320
72 hours at the local prison

45:40.440 --> 45:42.070
will give you a taste
of what awaits

45:42.190 --> 45:43.570
if you stray from your plan.

45:44.110 --> 45:45.610
Failure to graduate guarantees

45:45.740 --> 45:48.120
you serve
the sentence in full.

45:48.450 --> 45:50.370
You will be appointed
a probation officer

45:50.490 --> 45:51.750
to monitor your progress.

45:52.120 --> 45:53.210
Thank you, Council.

45:55.670 --> 45:56.540
That’s it?

45:56.670 --> 45:57.880
Yeah, you did great.

46:06.470 --> 46:08.970
You did it. I’m proud of you.

46:09.180 --> 46:10.350
I didn’t do anything.

46:10.470 --> 46:12.140
I stood there,
and kept my mouth shut.

46:12.600 --> 46:13.560
Exactly.

46:17.440 --> 46:18.650
So you knew the judge?

46:18.860 --> 46:20.020
Not really.

46:20.150 --> 46:21.320
Her daughter was in one of my

46:21.440 --> 46:24.150
performing arts
classes years ago.

46:25.320 --> 46:26.410
She’s on Broadway now.

46:27.450 --> 46:28.820
Sweet girl.

46:31.290 --> 46:35.540
You know, we can’t have you
sleeping on the couch anymore.

46:36.370 --> 46:37.420
Come on.

46:41.130 --> 46:43.170
I think you’ll be
more comfortable here.

46:44.170 --> 46:45.670
What about your mom’s stuff?

46:46.090 --> 46:47.630
This is your room now.

47:09.910 --> 47:11.120
What’s going on?

47:12.580 --> 47:13.540
What do you doing this weekend?

47:13.660 --> 47:14.370
Uh, nothing.

47:15.200 --> 47:18.290
God, Carl is such a douche.

47:18.790 --> 47:20.210
He thinks he’s Mr. Miami Vice,

47:20.330 --> 47:23.210
but he’s more like Donny
Osmond than he is Don Johnson.

47:27.720 --> 47:28.680
Maybe.

47:34.680 --> 47:35.850
They built the scene.

47:36.270 --> 47:38.060
Yeah. That’s good.

47:38.270 --> 47:39.190
-Yeah.
-Better.

47:40.350 --> 47:41.190
Nice.

47:42.270 --> 47:43.400
How’s the job hunt going?

47:43.520 --> 47:45.480
No, no one hires people
with a criminal record, Stan.

47:45.610 --> 47:46.280
I told you that.

47:46.400 --> 47:48.070
Okay, well,
it’s not gonna help, obviously,

47:48.240 --> 47:49.700
but get your grades up
and graduate.

47:49.820 --> 47:50.860
It will change.

47:52.030 --> 47:53.950
Hey, I could use your help.

47:54.410 --> 47:56.040
Building sets
for our new production.

47:56.160 --> 47:57.370
-There it is.
-What?

47:57.500 --> 47:58.370
You do want something from me.

47:58.500 --> 48:00.000
No, no. If I can’t
get a pay job,

48:00.120 --> 48:01.040
I have to work for my board.

48:01.170 --> 48:02.420
That’s not what I meant.

48:02.540 --> 48:04.340
That’s it, Stan. No, I’m not
interested in your stupid play.

48:04.460 --> 48:06.130
I’d say that’s pretty clear.

48:06.420 --> 48:07.170
Wait.

48:08.010 --> 48:09.130
Tina’s in this thing, right?

48:09.880 --> 48:11.010
-Yes, but--
-I’ll do it.

48:16.890 --> 48:18.390
You got this.

48:19.060 --> 48:20.560
This is just another
bump in the road.

48:21.730 --> 48:23.020
Remember, a year from now--

48:23.150 --> 48:23.900
Got it.

48:24.730 --> 48:26.400
This too shall pass.

48:34.490 --> 48:36.290
St. Bethany’s in ’73.

48:37.330 --> 48:38.950
That would have made you, six?

48:39.830 --> 48:40.620
Yeah.

48:41.210 --> 48:42.670
There till ’83,

48:42.790 --> 48:44.960
including four different
foster home placements.

48:46.460 --> 48:47.340
Okay.

48:47.920 --> 48:49.010
Where are you now?

48:49.840 --> 48:50.840
I’m with my teacher.

48:51.300 --> 48:52.220
Your teacher?

48:53.010 --> 48:54.220
What about your grandparents?

48:54.550 --> 48:55.930
No, they gave away custody.

48:56.390 --> 48:57.720
What about your
last foster parents?

48:58.020 --> 49:01.390
The-- was it the Williams?

49:01.850 --> 49:03.060
They should be
your legal guardians.

49:03.190 --> 49:03.980
No, you should be with them.

49:04.100 --> 49:06.020
No, no. The judge said
I could be with my teacher.

49:06.480 --> 49:07.440
It should be there.

49:07.570 --> 49:09.230
There’s no
record of that here.

49:10.190 --> 49:12.360
The Williams
are your guardians.

49:12.570 --> 49:13.280
You should be--

49:13.450 --> 49:15.030
Nah. They said
I could be with him.

49:15.160 --> 49:16.450
This is ridiculous.

49:16.620 --> 49:17.280
Hey, Viola!

49:17.620 --> 49:18.370
Yeah?

49:18.950 --> 49:21.460
I need some records
of the court case.

49:22.460 --> 49:23.330
Hey, Barney!

49:24.080 --> 49:24.750
Hey, Stan!

49:24.880 --> 49:26.540
Hey! How’s Maggie?

49:26.880 --> 49:28.090
Oh, I can’t complain.

49:28.210 --> 49:30.090
She started her own
business a few years back.

49:30.340 --> 49:31.670
You’re kidding.
That’s great.

49:32.090 --> 49:33.470
See, you met my student.

49:34.260 --> 49:36.390
He’s staying with me
till he gets back on his feet.

49:36.510 --> 49:37.890
The judge signed off on it.

49:38.060 --> 49:39.470
So he told me.

49:40.850 --> 49:43.560
Well, your teacher’s Stan Deen.

49:44.060 --> 49:45.350
Why didn’t you say so?

49:53.070 --> 49:55.160
Okay, so you’ve got
72 hours of prison time

49:55.280 --> 49:56.570
coming up in
the new year, right?

49:56.820 --> 49:57.530
Right.

49:57.660 --> 49:59.370
All right, check
in with me once a week.

50:00.080 --> 50:01.410
I run a tight ship.

50:04.790 --> 50:06.080
Is there anyone
you don’t know?

50:06.420 --> 50:07.580
Well, yes there is actually.

50:07.710 --> 50:08.840
I don’t know her.

50:09.590 --> 50:11.170
I don’t know them.
I don’t know her.

50:11.300 --> 50:12.260
Merry Christmas, Mr. Deen.

50:12.380 --> 50:14.050
Oh, Merry Christmas, Annabelle.

50:14.760 --> 50:16.510
-Right.
-We should be getting home.

51:40.970 --> 51:42.390
Keep going.

51:43.430 --> 51:45.520
Wow, good job.

51:45.640 --> 51:47.230
Look at those moves.

51:47.560 --> 51:49.850
You know who’s going to
be in my next musical, right?

51:50.440 --> 51:52.270
OK, guys, this is your set.

51:55.690 --> 51:57.240
It looks great.
Good job.

51:57.740 --> 51:58.820
Good job.

52:01.320 --> 52:02.910
And this is Algernon,
right?

52:19.090 --> 52:21.970
Merry Christmas, Nathan.
Ho, ho, ho.

52:23.890 --> 52:25.310
Who are all these presents for?

52:26.430 --> 52:27.350
They’re for you.

52:28.020 --> 52:29.100
All of them? They’re all mine?

52:29.310 --> 52:30.310
Let me check.

52:32.310 --> 52:35.980
Yours, yours,
yours, yours, yours.

52:36.690 --> 52:38.280
Yep, all yours.

52:38.610 --> 52:39.990
You bought all these for me?

52:40.360 --> 52:41.530
Of course.

52:46.330 --> 52:48.950
Nate. Nate!

52:50.410 --> 52:52.870
Now what?

54:50.120 --> 54:53.240
Nate. Get in the car.

54:57.750 --> 54:58.920
Nate.

55:00.880 --> 55:02.170
What’s wrong?

55:04.460 --> 55:05.720
It doesn’t matter.

55:07.760 --> 55:09.260
Why’d you do that, Stan?

55:09.390 --> 55:10.510
Buy all that shit?

55:11.180 --> 55:13.520
Is it--am I poor little homeless
boy? I’m a charity case?

55:13.640 --> 55:15.270
It would make you feel good?
What?

55:15.390 --> 55:19.480
No. Gosh, no. I mean,
I was trying to--

55:20.440 --> 55:22.650
You do know
it’s Christmas, right?

55:23.480 --> 55:24.820
I’ve never gotten
Christmas presents.

55:25.780 --> 55:27.150
You never got
a Christmas present?

55:28.660 --> 55:30.490
We used to do
underwear at the orphanage.

55:32.450 --> 55:33.330
Underwear?

55:35.080 --> 55:36.250
Oh, geez.

55:37.160 --> 55:38.160
Gosh darn it.

55:39.960 --> 55:40.880
I forgot underwear.

55:41.040 --> 55:42.790
Oh, God.
Everything’s not a joke.

55:43.170 --> 55:44.670
Stan, everything’s not funny.

55:44.800 --> 55:46.920
Okay. Okay.

55:48.090 --> 55:49.180
So why’d you do it?

55:50.220 --> 55:52.470
I was trying to
make you feel good, Nate.

55:54.010 --> 55:55.680
I want you to
have a good Christmas.

55:58.390 --> 55:59.140
That’s all.

55:59.270 --> 55:59.940
That’s all.

56:00.060 --> 56:01.270
Well, what else would it be?

56:01.440 --> 56:03.480
Bullshit. Stan,
everyone wants something back.

56:09.400 --> 56:11.950
You know, for eight years,
it’s just been me and my mom.

56:14.280 --> 56:16.540
She always said I smothered her.

56:17.000 --> 56:19.370
Stop it, Stan. Don’t fuss.

56:21.920 --> 56:25.920
I didn’t have anyone
to buy presents for this year.

56:26.170 --> 56:28.010
I guess I was
thinking about me.

56:29.090 --> 56:30.130
I’m sorry.

56:31.300 --> 56:32.510
I apologize.

56:33.850 --> 56:35.560
Merry Christmas,
Mr. Deen.

56:35.720 --> 56:38.020
Oh, Merry Christmas.

56:39.140 --> 56:40.520
Who was that?

56:41.140 --> 56:42.900
Please, can we get in the car?

56:45.020 --> 56:46.400
Have mercy.

56:49.440 --> 56:50.320
Right.

56:51.280 --> 56:54.280
Now I see how this might come
across as a little overboard.

56:54.740 --> 56:55.660
Yeah, you think?

56:56.530 --> 56:57.580
You know, I
didn’t get you anything.

56:58.080 --> 56:59.120
Actually, you did.

57:10.170 --> 57:12.050
Do--
Here. Here you go.

57:12.220 --> 57:13.590
Merry Christmas,
Stan.

57:13.720 --> 57:14.930
Merry Christmas, Stan.

57:15.140 --> 57:16.550
Thank you, Nate.

57:18.220 --> 57:19.350
What is it?

57:26.400 --> 57:27.770
Just what I wanted.

57:28.110 --> 57:29.360
Thank you, Nate.

57:31.440 --> 57:33.660
Right. Now let’s
get to the good part.

57:34.660 --> 57:36.240
Merry Christmas, Nate.

57:37.700 --> 57:39.290
You’re the weirdest person ever.

57:41.580 --> 57:44.330
Uh, you know that
Hershey bar you gave me?

57:44.670 --> 57:45.540
The one in class?

57:45.710 --> 57:46.460
Yeah.

57:47.170 --> 57:48.800
At the orphanage,

57:48.920 --> 57:51.840
when I first went to the
orphanage, I didn’t talk.

57:53.260 --> 57:55.130
For two years,
I just didn’t speak.

57:55.640 --> 57:57.430
And the keepers
would always bribe me

57:57.550 --> 57:59.060
with a candy bar
to get me to talk.

57:59.470 --> 58:01.930
And I never did.

58:02.560 --> 58:04.230
Never took it.
And I never talked, so.

58:06.150 --> 58:08.310
I know when you did that,
you didn’t want anything back.

58:08.820 --> 58:09.730
You know, so.

58:11.150 --> 58:12.070
Thank you.

58:12.650 --> 58:13.780
You’re welcome.

58:28.250 --> 58:29.290
Stan.

58:31.050 --> 58:32.840
Merry Christmas, Nate.

58:37.050 --> 58:38.930
Alice is an attractive
woman. She’s not married.

58:39.430 --> 58:40.310
And there’s nothing wrong.

58:40.470 --> 58:42.720
You stay away from
your sister’s friends.

58:42.970 --> 58:44.140
Do you hear me, Charlie?

58:44.430 --> 58:46.190
You’ve got to
stay away from girls.

58:46.440 --> 58:48.860
If you go near a girl,
I’m going to put you in a cage

58:48.980 --> 58:50.270
for the rest of your life.

58:50.650 --> 58:53.150
Do you hear me,
Charlie? Do you hear me?

58:53.280 --> 58:57.240
Okay, Carol. You need to be
really scary, okay?

58:57.990 --> 58:58.780
Look.

58:59.530 --> 59:02.120
When Charlie tries to be
romantic and close with Alice,

59:02.240 --> 59:04.250
he gets this
sudden memory of his mom

59:04.370 --> 59:06.960
being all mean
to him because as a kid,

59:07.210 --> 59:09.710
whenever he’d have those
feelings for any girl,

59:09.830 --> 59:12.960
that’s how she’d react, okay?
Really mean.

59:13.500 --> 59:16.380
So these memories,
they pop out of nowhere

59:16.510 --> 59:18.800
and it really frightens
Charlie, okay?

59:19.050 --> 59:20.090
Try again.

59:28.730 --> 59:30.560
Oh, rehearsal shots.

59:32.570 --> 59:34.360
Yeah, I thought they could
use them for the program.

59:34.480 --> 59:35.490
If they want.

59:35.650 --> 59:37.820
Oh, they’ll want.
These are good.

59:39.450 --> 59:40.700
Yeah, cool.

59:44.200 --> 59:47.410
These are good, Nate.
Where did you learn to do this?

59:48.040 --> 59:49.750
At a foster family I went to.

59:49.870 --> 59:51.330
One of the real kids
there had a camera

59:51.460 --> 59:52.750
and I stole it and used it.

59:53.090 --> 59:53.960
Real kids?

59:54.710 --> 59:56.010
Yeah, yeah.
That’s what we used

59:56.130 --> 59:57.220
to call them in the orphanage.

59:58.930 --> 01:00:00.430
What was the orphanage like?

01:00:01.510 --> 01:00:03.680
It was alright.
Keepers are okay.

01:00:04.220 --> 01:00:05.060
Keepers?

01:00:05.180 --> 01:00:08.230
Yeah, they ran it.
They tried their best.

01:00:10.100 --> 01:00:13.480
Do you remember your
home before that? Where it was?

01:00:14.770 --> 01:00:16.190
No, not really.

01:00:16.320 --> 01:00:19.200
My mom used to
call it Green Acres.

01:00:19.990 --> 01:00:21.320
After the TV show?

01:00:22.320 --> 01:00:23.030
Right.

01:00:23.660 --> 01:00:25.660
So was she like Eva Gabor?

01:00:28.410 --> 01:00:29.620
She was the star of the show.

01:00:29.750 --> 01:00:31.870
Very glamorous. Very beautiful.

01:00:33.210 --> 01:00:34.790
Yeah, yeah, I guess so,
yeah.

01:00:35.590 --> 01:00:36.800
She stood out. Remember that.

01:00:36.960 --> 01:00:39.220
We’d go out and people
would stare at her all the time.

01:00:40.170 --> 01:00:41.550
Remember feeling pretty cool.

01:00:42.800 --> 01:00:43.850
And your dad?

01:00:44.390 --> 01:00:46.060
Maybe that could be
the cover of the program.

01:00:46.850 --> 01:00:48.930
Hmm. Wonder why.

01:00:54.230 --> 01:00:58.530
Once more unto the breach,
dear friends, once more;

01:00:58.650 --> 01:01:02.700
Or close the wall up
with our English dead.

01:01:06.990 --> 01:01:08.240
Nathan...

01:01:08.450 --> 01:01:10.660
We’re gonna play a
new game tonight, okay?

01:01:10.790 --> 01:01:11.960
It’s gonna be a lot of fun.

01:01:12.080 --> 01:01:14.290
We’re gonna run,
really, really fast.

01:01:14.420 --> 01:01:16.500
As far as we can,
for as long as we can.

01:01:16.630 --> 01:01:19.340
And we’re not gonna stop
until I say so, okay?

01:01:20.050 --> 01:01:23.340
You can do that?
You promise me? Okay.

01:01:25.260 --> 01:01:26.300
Okay, c’mon sweetie.

01:01:26.430 --> 01:01:28.350
Gloria,
come on down.

01:01:30.180 --> 01:01:31.600
Nathan, hurry.

01:01:31.890 --> 01:01:33.140
Come on, quicker.

01:01:33.770 --> 01:01:35.770
Run now, baby, run.

01:02:31.490 --> 01:02:32.790
I can’t help you.
Mom...

01:02:58.230 --> 01:02:59.560
Look.

01:03:01.150 --> 01:03:03.110
It’s so calm and peaceful.

01:03:03.990 --> 01:03:05.610
And we’ll be
together forever.

01:03:21.130 --> 01:03:22.300
Gloria!

01:03:55.910 --> 01:04:01.630
Hey, looking for
newspapers from like early 1973.

01:04:01.750 --> 01:04:03.040
Would you have those?

01:04:09.130 --> 01:04:10.090
Thank you.

01:04:30.400 --> 01:04:33.490
